description.text:
Pwdr is an open source powder-based rapid prototyping machine. Its goal is to promote experiments and innovations in powder-based rapid-prototyping. The machine is ready to use both the 3DP as the SLS process with minimal adaption, although the printer is currently prepped for 3DP. More information on: http://pwdr.github.com Hardware
The Pwdr Model 0.1 consists of chassis, tool head and electronics. The printer entirely consists of off-the-shelf components. It has a simple design and can be built within a couple of hours. The machine is easy and affordable to build and modify. Building a Pwdr Model 0.1 machine costs about â‚¬1000,-. Software
The accompanying software for the Pwdr Model 0.1 converts the CAD model in a printable format. This file is then uploaded to the Pwdr Model 0.1 micro-controller. The machine is controlled by easy-to-use software that allow full control of the printing process.The Pwdr Model 0.1 software has been based on open source tools like Arduino and Processing. Materials
A whole new range of materials become available for experimenting with open-source rapid-prototyping; for example, when using the 3DP process: gypsum, ceramics, concrete, sugar, etc. And when the SLS process is fully supported, plastic materials like ABS, PP, Nylon and metals become available as building material.A Hewlett Packard inkjet cartridge is used for the deposition of binder. The cartridge can be refilled with custom binders using a syringe. A custom binder of 20% alcohol and 80% water has been proven to work. Specifications
  • Maximum build size: 125mm x 125mm x 125mm
  • Print resolution (3DP): 96DPI
  • Minimum vertical step size: 50Î¼m
  • Speed (depending on printed part): Â±1 minute per layer

Manual Pwdr Model 0.1 Machine Hardware
The printer consists of two bins (#1 for storing powder, near electronics and #2 for building the part), which move up and down respectfully during the printing process. The powder is bonded using a standard inkjet printer head. Steppers
The steppers that accommodate the movements are controlled via stepper boards that send the correct voltage and current. When a stepper â€˜misses stepsâ€™, the maximum current must be adjusted. Turn the white pot-meter of the corresponding stepper board clockwise to increase the maximum current. Note: when the maximum current is set too high, the stepper is bound to overheat. When this happens, disconnect power and let the stepper cool. Drive belts
The drive belts transmit the movements from the steppers to the carriages. To tighten them up, just turn the adjustment screws. When the belts are extended completely, adjust the belts length at the belt clamps. Printer head
The printer head that deposits the binder is a standard Hewlett Packard C6602A cartridge. Itâ€™s connected to the Arduino micro-controller via a custom protoshield board that supplies the correct voltages to the nozzles. The nozzles are prone to breaking when a wrong voltage is applied. Therefore, the power supply to the protoshield should only be connected when printing. To avoid powder to stick to the nozzles, please put a small sellotape strip in the front of the cartridge. To enable refilling of the cartridge, remove the label on top of the cartridge; it covers the vents. A syringe with a custom binder can be mounted in the front vent, as described later. Software
Two pieces of software are used for the printer control; the firmware running on the Arduino micro-controller and control software running on a computer. The control software handles the conversion of the CAD-model to a print file as well as the communication with the printer. Micro-controller firmware
The firmware running on the Arduino micro-controller controls all actuators. The print file is stored on itâ€™s internal memory. This means that every new print file must be uploaded to the micro-controller using the Arduino IDE. The print files are made by the preprocessor. Preprocessor / Pwdr_GUI_V2.0
The client software is written in Processing. To run the program, you need the Processing environment. When the client software is run, it opens in the preprocessor mode. Here, you can choose the model you want to print and convert it to a print file. The print files are saved in the folder â€˜Arduino/PwdrFirmwareâ€™ along the main firmware file. To upload the print files, open the Arduino IDE and click â€˜compile and uploadâ€™. Note: the client software needs a serial line for communication with the micro-controller. Fill in the correct serial port number on line 87 of â€˜Pwdr_GUI_V2.0.ideâ€™, the available ports are shown in the verbose output of the Processing IDE when the file is run. When the correct port number is edited, itâ€™s possible to compile the program to a standalone version which doesnâ€™t need the Processing IDE to run. Control software / Pwdr_GUI_V2.0
When the button â€˜printâ€™ is clicked in the preprocessor, the client software switches to control mode. Here, you can jog the various actuators and control the machine. To start a print job, simply click â€˜printâ€™. Printing workflow
Make sure that the power supply is disconnected To prevent the ink cartridge from burning, the power supply for the cartridge (and preferably the power supply for the stepper too) must be disconnected when data is sent to the Arduino micro-controller. Convert model to printable data
Open the Pwdr_GUI Processing program. Make sure the Arduino micro-controller is connected. Run the program. Fill the correct serial port number (listed in the Processing verbose window) in on line 86 of Pwdr_GUI_V2.0.pde. Stop the program and run again. Open up the file that is due to be printed. Click â€˜convert modelâ€™. Make sure the file has a height divisible by 12. Otherwise, a verbose message will be shown. Click â€˜send print fileâ€™. The two files with print data (â€˜PwdrPrintData.inoâ€™ and â€˜PwdrPrintDataUpper.inoâ€™) are now saved to a folder called â€˜Arduinoâ€™. Note: Currently, the only way to change the parameters is by hardcoding them in the Processing parameter declarations (saturation, file height, etc.). These parameters are included in the print file that is send to the micro-controller. Sent printable data to micro-controller
Open the machineâ€™s firmware (â€˜PwdrFirmware.inoâ€™). When opening, the two print files should be displayed as tabs. Click â€˜compile and uploadâ€™. The firmware is now compiled and sent to the Arduino micro-controller. Note: Currently, the only way to change the parameters is by hardcoding them in the Arduino parameter declarations (step-sizes, margins, etc.). Clean machine and reset position
Thoroughly clean the machine using a vacuum cleaner, brushes, etc. Degrease the roller using cloth soaked with alcohol or thinner. Makes sure the guidance rods are lubed and the belt drives are tensioned correctly. Move the XY-carriage , by hand, to the far end (opposite of the motors) of the machine. The X-carriage should touch the axis of the roller stepper. Filling up with powder and binder
Adjust the position of the pistons using the control software. Fill the bins with powder and make sure to tap it quite firmly so a very solid base arises. Press extra hard on the powder near the edges. Scrape the excess amount of powder off. You can move (when the power is disconnected) the XY-carriage across the bins to check whether enough powder has been applied. Make sure to move it to itâ€™s initial position afterwards. When the binder has run out, premix a solution of 20% alcohol and 80% (demi) water. Put the mixture in a syringe and fit a 22G needle. Stick the needle in the vent op top of the cartridge and remove the syringeâ€™s piston so the binder can flow freely in the cartridge. Make sure no binder leaks out of the cartridge. Connect power
Now the program is uploaded to the micro-controller, itâ€™s safe to connect the power to both the stepper and cartridge supplies. But first, run the â€˜Pwdr_GUI_V2.0â€™ program, click â€˜printâ€™ and wait for the verbose message â€˜Safe to connect powerâ€™. Note; Each time software connects with the Arduino micro-controller, itâ€™s rebooted. During reboot, random voltages are applied to random ports, possibly hurting the ink cartridges. Deposit a number of layers fresh powder
Because the hand-filled power has another porosity and density than the machine-laid powder, deposited a number of layers (Â±5) by the machine. Click the button â€˜make new layerâ€™. Initialize XY-carriage position
Initialize the position of the XY-carriage by clicking the â€˜initial positionâ€™ button. The XY-carriage moves to the starting point. When for whatever reason this position should be changed, use the jog controls. When the position has been adjusted, click â€˜reset positionsâ€™. Start print job
Now, the machine is completely ready to start printing. Click â€˜printâ€™ to start the print job. The verbose messages show the printing progress. Note: When something is wrong and the printing process should be canceled immediately, press the emergency button on the prototype board (the button with a black cross). After this, disconnect power and close the control software. Finish print job
When the print process has finished, deposit a few layers on top of the printed product, this helps binding the last printed layers. Leave the printed part to rest a couple of hours to let the binder fully penetrate and bind the powder. Remove printed part
When the part has hardened a couple of hours, itâ€™s safe to remove it from the build platform. Use a brush to carefully remove powder from the edges. When the parts outline has been fully revealed, use a scoop or spatula to carefully take out the part. Make sure not the apply load or torque on the part. When the part is eviscerated, remove excess powder with a brush. The part is now ready for post-processing (e.g. sintering or fixating using cyanoacrylate).

A (customizable) cryptex I designed. I mainly invested quite some time in creating haptic feedback of the rings.

Simply print top_ring, bottom_ring, one of the available bases (4,5,6,7 letters), all letters you need and the same amount of internal rings. Use some super glue to attach the separate parts.
Edit: as Jaybob08 suggested, its also possible to melt the parts together. Use a soldering iron to melt the edges together!.

Edit: Instructions for gluing:

  1. Take the bottom ring (bottom_ring.stl)
  2. Glue one of the internal rings (internal_ring.stl) to the bottom ring. Make sure that the notches of both rings are aligned.
  3. Place the outer ring, belonging to the last letter of your keyword to the internal ring of step 2.
  4. Take a new internal ring and glue this one to the internal ring of step 2 in such a way that the internal rings are glued together, but the outer ring can rotate freely.
  5. Repeat step 3 and 4 until you have placed all internal rings and outer rings.
  6. Glue the top ring (top_ring.stl) to the final internal ring.
    Note: Be careful with gluing, you absolutely want to avoid gluing any of the outer rings. This results in a non-functioning cryptex.

description.text:
After designing the teardrop shape enclosures for the Dayon PS95's, I decided to tackle the Overnight Sensations. I built my first Overnight Sensations kit back in 2010 and have been very happy with them ever since. Once I bought a CR-10 I knew I'd want to eventually make a pair of enclosures for them, and here they are. I initially finished this design a couple of months ago, and presented them at DIY Iowa 2017. I'm just getting around to uploading it now.

I want to preface this with the fact that this was an experiment, as most things in life are. It really isn't the best enclosure design. It won't be an improvement over Paul Carmody's original design (who can seriously improve on his stuff though?) Some will argue that a spherical enclosure is the best design for a speaker enclosure (I based this design off of that theory) however my design has one flaw to it. The port is located right behind the 4" driver, so half of the mid range just goes straight out the back. If you do end up printing this, have fun with it, but keep that fact in mind. I also want to note that while the enclosure shape has changed, the internal volume and port volume have stayed true to Paul's original design.

That's pretty much my short story. I printed it at 0.2mm layer height and it took about 70 hours per side. You could probably improve on this time, however I was in no rush when printing them. Make sure you print it baffle side down (I'm not sure how the STL is oriented in the file) and also you'll need support material for the baffle mount, as well as for the port.

Any questions, please leave a comment. If you do end up printing them, I'd love to see pictures! Thanks.

title: Flat cable chain mod for Anet A8

description.text:
I printed out and installed Starwhooper's Improved Linear Chain to Extruder on Anet A8 (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1905344) and also davbarr's Z_Motor_Fixation_Chain for Anet A8 (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2055872).

Like a lot of users the chain would pop out of the z-axis mount and curve upwards and not stay flat and parallel when the x-axis carriage was moving. So I designed this mod, to hold the chain flat and parallel when attached to the z-axis mount.

It uses a medium chain piece from Starwhooper and lifts the connection higher to provide a more parallel run for the chain to the extruder, along with bracing it against x-axis mount to prevent vertical twisting.

This part can be printed without support and is designed to slip over the cable, so no need to disconnect the cables and thread it through any parts.

I added a cable tie to mine to keep the joint tight and secure (see photos), it works well for me and keeps my chain flat. I printed it at 0.3 resolution to save time, but it would look better at 0.2.

This has been tested on an Anet A8 but might work for other printers.

So I've gotten a lot of emails over the last two years from people who suffer from hand tremors or know close friends/family that do and would like to see updates for this design. I have news... sorta, in an engineering course I worked with a group of several students to improve this design and make it manufacturable. the improved design is more stable from a physics standpoint but doesn't use any 3D printed parts. I am working to adapt the design to a printable form factor and publish it online for all to use. So these were created for a science fair project I did with the objective to try to develop several different types of drinking cups for people with parkinsons or suffer from a severe intention tremor. My grandfather, who has a severe intention tremor, burned himself trying to drink coffee one day and thats what inspired me to create these cups. I only had my printer for a month before the fair, so I did not get to develop these as much as I had hoped to. In a later version there may be orientation locks, turning limits (so you can actually drink from it), and more standardized weights. That seems to trick it into drawing thinner walls and worked for me - though I did have to file a little to get the recesses for the header to fit.

Customization Options.

You can add keys on either side, though if your keys are subsets or mirrors of each other, they still might fit other sockets.

You can have thinner walls with more secure keys if you choose to locate them where you do NOT have a wire.

This is intended for common 0.1" / 2.54mm headers. You can put the male or female sides in either the plug or the housing, they're the same size.

Assembly

It took me a bit of effort to get the black header pins into the printed plug thing. I had to sand a little, and then press on a hard surface.

The other "catch" is that the "housing" that the plug goes in is also kind of tight. So if it's not glued to the header strip, then pulling the plug off the header will remove the housing as well (which sort of defeats the purpose of the keys).

description.text:
This is my first real “3D printed anything” that I had something to do with, so proceed with caution. I am not buying you replacement filament if this doesn’t work……

First off, all the credit for the brilliant ideas go to feenix82. The layout, cable management, measurements are all his. I chose to remix this because my printer or settings or me struggled to get the venting to work right. While I was in there, I made the walls higher in hopes that I can make a flat cover rather than a cover with walls. I also added some uprights to the side tabs, and added some pretty filleting that I might regret.

I will eventually post the source files which I had to make from scratch. I basically imported the mesh (which imported huge and not to the right scale) then I traced it for the measurements and layout. After I discovered the scaling issue… after I spent an hour or so tracing... I re-scaled it. The cable management I redid with patterns because it would have taken a week to do that manually. The vents were also completed manually. I got a bit OCD about symmetry. so, I made some changes to the vents.

UPDATE: lots of little tweaks.
-added 40mm side fan
-added some fillets to the cable management for strength
-reduced the depth of the cover holes because they didn't need to be 50mm deep.
-raised the posts for the main board by 5mm to help with some clearances for the power input of the main board. (seems like there may be some conflicts)
-had microscopic gaps between the top parts of the cable management loops.
raised the side walls to be 51mm total. hope that clears the heat sinks on the external mosfets. I also stretched the vent holes to match this adjustment.
-left version 1 in there in case someone wants the old version
Edit: V2 had a mistake in the port holes. When I raised the main board, I did not raise the USB and SD card openings.

UPDATE 020518: Had some issues with printing. I actually think this was a combination of print settings and suspect PLA.. The issues I had were with the circuit board posts. These were being made in a flimsy way. Seems when it is being sliced, it will do one layer of the wall for each post then return for another layer. This means it needs to start and stop dropping its bead of filament. Since I have not figured out a super elegant way of making this work well. I linked some posts together to try to force it to do what I want.

note about the cable management... I did find that if I sent the supports overhang to 88*, that it spans the gaps successfully without supports. This will be much easier to crack out the supports.

UPDATE 021118: Had lots of trouble with the cable loops. So i modified the drawing to loose the loops, and add holes in the place instead. there is also a bracket that will click into these loops. my thought was that printing these later would speed up the print, reduce retractions, and also allow me to print those horizontally rather than vertically so that they print stronger. i could also print them in a different color which might be cool.

I will be working on the top cover soon, but wanted to get to a proper test print first. because the box is deeper, the cover can be made simply flat. should make printing easier. i also have a fan on the side, so i will not make a fan for the front.

UPDATE 021318: Was able to successfully print. Super pleased with the outcome. The cable clips glued in with CA glue very nicely. plenty of room for the cables. Will post a cover soon.

After fixing the zipper case, using the very same rope to fix the TN spine with the same manner and make sure the rope get through the hole on each end of the TN spine.

description.text:
EDIT 7-24-2016
So I've gotten a lot of emails over the last two years from people who suffer from hand tremors or know close friends/family that do and would like to see updates for this design. I have news... sorta, in an engineering course I worked with a group of several students to improve this design and make it manufacturable. the improved design is more stable from a physics standpoint but doesn't use any 3D printed parts. I am working to adapt the design to a printable form factor and publish it online for all to use. So these were created for a science fair project I did with the objective to try to develop several different types of drinking cups for people with parkinsons or suffer from a severe intention tremor. My grandfather, who has a severe intention tremor, burned himself trying to drink coffee one day and thats what inspired me to create these cups. I only had my printer for a month before the fair, so I did not get to develop these as much as I had hoped to. In a later version there may be a better handle, better fluid containment, less of a pressure difference upon pivot, increased degrees of freedom. Heres the catch, If I hear that any one of you makermen and women think that this is a great idea, and say so in the comments, then I will complete my designs for these cups more proactively. In the fluid series I have developed a unique mug that is intended to use a non-newtonian (shear-thinning) to simulate a slosh tank (what they use to counter earthquake vibrations in tall buildings) within a large outer apparatus. As a result the inner cup pivots in the opposite direction to counter the effect of some minor translational and rotational oscillations due to hand tremors. My axis series: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:277956

The Non-newtonian fluid I used was a silicone lubricant, It demonstrated the desired effect for shear-thinning which I believed would most benefit the design. however, I think plain old water my also work, as long as the fluid in the inner cup isn't particularly dense. There is a cap for the bottom included because there was seepage in my design. just glue one of these things to it and you should be fine. (yes I know its ugly, but the whole thing is anyway) I printed with PLA
.4 fill
3 layers, everywhere
.2 think If you are considering using these products then I recommend
4 layers on top
solid infil every few layers
<.2 thinkness
and vapor polish it

I designed this based on the stock Anet A8 extruder, which has issues feeding TPU due to the distance from the gear to the output hole. I have tested with TPU and it prints like a champ! It should easily attach to any stepper mount, and as such be useful to more than just the Anet A8. Coupled with a pancake stepper it will be an incredibly small extruder solution!

Please let me know in comments how it goes for you, and if there is anything you think would need to be changed. I will take every suggestion into consideration.

Print settings:
25% Cubic infill
0.2 Layers
3 Walls / Top and Bottom layers
Supports everywhere - 10% Lines in Cura - Only needed for the 'Right' side and 'Retainer'.

I printed the objects how they stand in the STL for strength against the spring. The shaft which the 625 bearing goes on should be the strongest in this orientation.

Required parts:
Various M3 bolts, length will vary depending on your choice of mount.
1 x M3 Nut
1 x M3 Washer
1 x M4 bolt - I used the one from the A8 extruder
2 x (or more depending on spring tension) M4 nuts
1 x 625 Bearing
2 x F623zz Bearings (Stock A8 belt idler bearings)
1 x MK7 Extruder gear (Other gears should work too but this is the one I use)
1 x Extruder / Heatbed Spring (approx 8mm diameter / 20mm length)
2 x PC4M6 Pneumatic Couplings

Assembly:
Should be fairly self explanatory, Trap a nut in the back of the 'Right' piece which will be on the back of the 625 bearing shaft. Put a M3 washer on the bolt which goes through 'Right' piece F623zz bearing to space it from the stepper mount. I have allowed 0.5mm for this washer. To align the drive gear, I first mounted the 'Right' piece and then aligned with the feed hole.

Post Process:
You will want to bore the feed and output holes to 2mm with a drill bit to ensure they are smooth.
You may need to file the flat edge on the 'Retainer' piece so that it properly fits into the top of the 'Right' piece depending on your printers tolerances.
The M3 hole in the 'Right' piece may need to be made slightly larger to ensure free movement.
Oral B - Head holder. Stick with double-sided tape.

description.text:
Yet another Raspberry Pi top case designed to work with the ubiquitous 0110-M-P RasPi VESA case, but directly remixed from the Alternate top case for Raspberry Pi with Razberry Z-wave module as that has a solid top surface.

I wanted to have a case lid for my raspi to which I could attach one of my PCB prototype boards without going so far as to getting a complete hat as I only needed a couple pins connected. I needed the solid top surface, and had to raise the overall case top 5mm to get clearance for the DuPont connectors inside the case. For my particular use, I've got three rows of female DuPont header with all the pins on each soldered together and a 4.7k resistor between two - I then connect these to the raspi on 3v3, GND, and GPIO 4, which allows me to plug in DS18B20 temperature sensors which have been soldered to 1x3 DuPont male connectors. It's a compact and efficient way to hook up multiple DS18B20 sensors. kinda like three rows of a breadboard.

In the first photo you can see I've got three sensors connected - one directly (although the connection is a bit hit or miss without the proper connector) and two on the end of cables - one is a DIY cable and the other is a store-bought waterproof DS18B20.

The last photo shows the wiring underneath the lid with the PCB.

One additional thing worth mentioning - during my searches I came across the Terminal Block Case which uses this awesome terminal block hat for the RasPi - it wasn't exactly what I needed for this project, but it makes connecting wiring to the raspi so wonderfully easy, I thought that it merited mention here, as it might turn out to be more useful to you than my design.

title: Interchangeable  FPV Pan/Tilt Camera Mount for RC Models

description.text:
Howdy, are you looking for an interchangeable pan or pan & tilt system for FPV, with platforms for a Mobius or RunCam 2 HD camera?

The pan axis will accept a standard 9g or 12g servo or ideally a 180 degree servo such as the Turnigy TGY-180D. As for the tilt, a decent metal geared servo is suggested.

UPDATE: There are two extra files which include pre-made supports for your ease of printing & a video of them is here https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ABXVgXuacas

Built Tips:

  • Parts are best printed in tougher materials such as ABS or carbon laced filament.
  • Drilling the holes out with a 3.0mm drill makes for a smoother tilt action.
  • M3 plastic or metal bolts & nuts (14mm or longer) are needed to secure the tilt platform.
  • Work on getting the pan dome to slide as close as possible to the base (almost a friction fit), so the pan/tilt part does not rock. This will save excessive stress being put onto you pan servo when landing
  • Printing an extra base and making a "sandwich of foam" is a great way of providing a secure way of holding the top pan/tilt system in place and through thinner layers of foam

Created by Andrew Boulton, his YouTube channel is here https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCLv1vkEDIDWzac0UaVG2YRQ

Check the license for these parts, attribution is required and NO commercial deviations.

It was a hassle needing to disassemble the filastruder if I wanted to take the hopper off, or change it to horizontal, and I like the two piece removable hoppers. The hopper has a slot in the front for keeping track of the level of pellets.  I cut a piece from a clear plastic report cover to make the window.  A cap helps keep moisture out, and the underside would be a good place to stick a desiccant cartridge with some double sided tape.

description.text: I was frustrated with small calibration targets that required measurement of 10-40 mm.  My thought that was stepper error would be compounded over longer lengths.  So I created a 120 mm target.  The minor axis is 15mm.  The thickness is 3mm. Perhaps someone has done this already...and I'm happy to give credit where credit is due.

Print and measure while still attached to the bed to avoid distortion from extraction.
Traditionally, all other things being equal, on smaller calibrations, say for a 10, 20, or 40 mm theoretical measurement, a +1% error would result in actual measurements of 10.1, 20.2, or 40.4 mm, whereas this print would provide a measurement of 121.2 mm.  I don't know about you, but discerning an error of 1.2 mm is a lot easier than one that is 400 microns, especially when you factor in the anisotropic thermal distortions in the extruded part.  Compared to the 40 mm calibration your sensitivity goes up by a factor of three.
Other thoughts and perspectives much appreciated.

description.text:
This is a simple and effective z-belt linking mod originally created by nselimis and modified by me. Enjoy!

Changes:

  • Created a shorter version for 696 mm GT2 belts.
  • Modified M3 holes to accept hex nuts whereas the original design requires screwing machine screws directly into the print.
  • Tweaked the tensioner dimensions so the tension screw won't hit the idler pulley screw.
  • Created an anti-slip pocket in the base for the tension screw.

Required hardware:

  • (1) (760 mm or 696 mm) closed loop GT2 Belt
  • (2) 5mm bore double-headed GT2 belt pulleys (http://a.co/0pWd3dl)
  • (3) 3mm bore GT2 belt idler pulleys
  • (4) M3 hex nuts
  • (1) M3x25 screw*
  • (2) M3x20 screws**
  • (1) M3x16 screw
  • (2) #6x1/2 inch wood screws

*= This is simply the minimum recommended size. I'm using an M3x40 screw in my photos.
**= M3x18 should work too.

Assembly tips:

  • Because I have vibration dampers on my z-axis motors, I found that I had to flip the gear pulleys attached to the leadscrews to get the belt aligned to the double-headed gear pulleys.
  • Before tensioning the new belt, level the print bed by hand first. Then, using the LCD interface, move the z-axis down 1 mm. Doing so should lock your z-axis in place and prevent unleveling the bed while you tension the bracket.

This is a dice tray for Doctor Who: Time of the Daleks, with a sliding dovetail lid and 8 spaces to fit dice. A dice blocker model is included to take up dice spaces depending on Daleks and time anomalies. The sliding lid has two notches on one side so it will stay shut when fully closed.
